{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657802","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657802"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:35:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:35:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20652"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20652","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20652"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13528"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95009"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13528","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13528"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20652"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77983"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11585"},{"type":"tags","id":"11782"},{"type":"tags","id":"12538"},{"type":"tags","id":"12540"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32306"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32307"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32308"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95009","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/95009"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EFibrosis is a pathological process that can occur in various organs following chronic injury or inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the pathophysiological process of fibrosis in parenchymal organs?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Excessive deposition of collagen and extracellular matrix components","Formation of new blood vessels in damaged tissue","Replacement of damaged tissue with adipose tissue","Uncontrolled proliferation of parenchymal cells","Accumulation of inflammatory cells without resolution"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Eexcessive deposition of collagen and extracellular matrix components\u003C/strong\u003E. Fibrosis is characterised by the abnormal accumulation of extracellular matrix proteins, particularly collagen, in response to tissue injury. This process shares the same basic mechanisms as scar formation in the skin during tissue repair but becomes pathological when excessive or persistent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFormation of new blood vessels in damaged tissue\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes angiogenesis, which may occur during tissue repair but is not the defining feature of fibrosis.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReplacement of damaged tissue with adipose tissue\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes a process called fatty replacement or steatosis, which is different from fibrosis.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUncontrolled proliferation of parenchymal cells\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes hyperplasia or neoplasia rather than fibrosis. In fibrosis, there is often a loss of parenchymal cells that are replaced by fibrous tissue.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAccumulation of inflammatory cells without resolution\u003C/strong\u003E - While inflammation often precedes fibrosis, the hallmark of fibrosis is the excessive deposition of extracellular matrix, not persistent inflammation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFibrotic disorders can affect multiple organ systems and include conditions such as liver cirrhosis, systemic sclerosis, idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis, end-stage kidney disease, and constrictive pericarditis. The excessive fibrosis in these conditions can lead to substantial organ dysfunction and even organ failure, making them targets for antifibrotic drug development.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Fibrosis refers to excessive deposition of collagen and other extracellular matrix components in tissue, which can lead to organ dysfunction or failure.","The mechanisms of fibrosis are similar to those of scar formation in the skin during tissue repair.","Fibrotic disorders affect multiple organ systems including liver, lungs, kidneys, and heart, causing significant morbidity."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 3, Inflammation and Repair; p. 110"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77983"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20652"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77983","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/77983"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-26T20:57:07+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-26T21:00:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13528"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95009"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11585","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11585"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Inflammation and repair","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":2,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T15:14:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T15:14:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11782","links":